@NODE Pattern  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Search pattern@{ub}

Use this stringgadget to enter your search pattern. Use wildcards like
this, when doing a @{" Normal Search " LINK Modes} :

  '.' = any character

  '*' = any number of any characters


If you activate the gadget by pressing Shift-P the contents are cleared.


These @{" Examples " LINK Examples} will explain a lot.



See also @{" Expected gadget " LINK Expected}
         @{" Keys            " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Listview  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Search results@{ub}

This is where all search results are presented. If there are more then
20 results scroll the listview with the slider or use the arrow-gadgets.

Zuppel checks also during a search for updating information of the
listview, so you can look at the beginning of the list while Zuppel
continues the search.



See also @{" Clear     " LINK Clear}
         @{" Autoclear " LINK Autoclear}
         @{" Keys      " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Search  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Search@{ub}

This is one of the most important buttons. After you have entered a valid
@{" Search pattern " LINK pattern}, clicking Search will start the search.

It will search the entire @{" Wordlist " LINK Wordlist} for the given pattern and store
all matches in the @{" Search results " LINK listview} listview.
You can select the type of search by clicking the @{" SearchMode " LINK Modes} button.


To interrupt the search operation click @{" Break " LINK Break}.



See also @{" SearchModes " LINK Modes}
         @{" Break       " LINK Break}
         @{" Examples    " LINK Examples}
         @{" Keys        " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Normal  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Normal Search@{ub}

The Normal Search will search the @{" Wordlist " LINK Wordlist} for words matching the search
pattern. Use wildcards like this:

  '.' = any character

  '*' = any number of any characters


Use this mode to search words for your crosswords!


To interrupt the search operation click @{" Break " LINK Break}.



See also @{" SearchModes " LINK Modes}
         @{" Break       " LINK Break}
         @{" Examples    " LINK Examples}
         @{" Keys        " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE AnaSearch  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Anagram Search@{ub}

The @{" Search pattern " LINK pattern} may NOT contain any wildcards when doing an Anagram
search, meaning you may not enter any '.' and '*' characters in the pattern.

The Anagram search will search the @{" Wordlist " LINK Wordlist} for words containing exactly
the same characters as the search pattern, regardless of their position
within the examined word.

To interrupt the search operation click @{" Break " LINK Break}.



See also @{" SearchModes " LINK Modes}
         @{" Break       " LINK Break}
         @{" Examples    " LINK Examples}
         @{" Keys        " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Contain  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Contain Search@{ub}

The @{" Search pattern " LINK pattern} may NOT contain any wildcards when doing a Contain
Search, meaning you may not enter any '.' and '*' characters in the pattern.

The Contain Search will search the @{" Wordlist " LINK Wordlist} for words contained by the
search pattern. One could call the results 'sub-words'.

To interrupt the search operation click @{" Break " LINK Break}.



See also @{" SearchModes " LINK Modes}
         @{" Break       " LINK Break}
         @{" Examples    " LINK Examples}
         @{" Keys        " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Shuffle  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Shuffle Search@{ub}

The @{" Search pattern " LINK pattern} may NOT contain any wildcards when doing a Shuffle
Search, meaning you may not enter any '.' and '*' characters in the pattern.

The Shuffle search will search the @{" Wordlist " LINK Wordlist} for words containing chars
also contained by the the search pattern, regardless of their position.
Meaning, it tries to make new words from the characters of the search
pattern.

Use this mode when you're playing Scrabble ®

To interrupt the search operation click @{" Break " LINK Break}.



See also @{" SearchModes " LINK Modes}
         @{" Break       " LINK Break}
         @{" Examples    " LINK Examples}
         @{" Keys        " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Modes  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - SearchModes@{ub}

The SearchModes cyclegadget is placed below the Search button.
It contains the following modes:

  @{" Normal  " LINK Normal}
  @{" Anagram " LINK AnaSearch}
  @{" Contain " LINK Contain}
  @{" Shuffle " LINK Shuffle}



See also @{" Keys " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Break  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Break@{ub}

This button is normally disabled but becomes enabled during a search operation.

When enabled, you can stop the search immediately by clicking it.

This may be useful if your wordlist is alphabetically ordered and the first
character of your search pattern is not a wildcard. Then if all matches are
found but Zuppel is looking for other matches you can break the search.

Or use it if your search pattern doesn't come up with the words you want..



See also @{" Keys " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE SaveResults  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Save Results@{ub}

After a @{" Search " LINK Search} or @{" Anagram search " LINK Anasearch} operation you can save the search
results in a file.

A standard filerequester will be opened and you may enter a filename to
store the results in. If the file already exists you will be asked what to
do.

Choose:

  Append  to append the results at the end of the file.
  Replace to replace the file. Be aware that the chosen file will be
          overwritten!
  Cancel  to cancel the whole Save results operation.



See also @{" Search Results " LINK Listview}
         @{" Keys           " LINK Keys}
         @{" Configuration  " LINK Configuration}

@endnode


@NODE Wordlist  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Wordlist@{ub}

This button opens a filerequester where you can enter the filename of the
wordlist to be used. The chosen file will be active untill you choose
another.

The format of the wordlist file is simple: it is an ASCII file containing
one word on every line. The maximum length of one word is currently 50
characters but can be changed on @{" Request " LINK Author}.

To test if a wordlist is compatible with Zuppel enter just an * as the
@{" Search pattern " LINK pattern} and compare the words in the Search results with
the words in the file by using an external text viewer such as multiview.
(Be careful with big files loading into Multiview. It certainly will crash
your whole system if it can't handle the file!!)

If you encounter a € character at the end of each word, you have to convert
the file. The file you have is created on a PC running MS-DOS and thus
contains a CR character at the end of each line. Remove them by using my
tool F#ckPC or CrossDOS or a simple texteditor.


There are currently 2 wordlists supplied with Zuppel. A Dutch one grabbed
from the internet and an English one from an old PD wordprocessor. The
latter was converted to ASCII by me.


If the wordlist fits into RAM (i.e. the largest block of available RAM is
more than the filesize) you will be asked if the wordlist should be loaded
in RAM or not. It is recommended to load it at once, regarding the gain of
speed. It's about 30% faster because disk I/O is slower than RAM.


Hint:

If your memory is fragmented and therefore Zuppel couldn't read the
wordlist in RAM, copy it to the Ramdisk and choose the copy in RAM as
wordlist. This speeds up a little, but not as much as when Zuppel would
load it into RAM because now the RAM I/O slows down the reading (it's a RAM
DISK remember, not a block of RAM, so system read-routines are still called
to do a read..)



Other wordlists can be found on the internet:

gopher://gopher.lysator.liu.se/00/project-runeberg/dict/where



See also @{" Thanx         " LINK Thanx}
         @{" Keys          " LINK Keys}
         @{" Configuration " LINK Configuration}

@endnode


@NODE Clear  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Clear@{ub}

Clicking Clear will clear the @{" Search results " LINK listview} listview.

Clear is disabled when @{" Autoclear " LINK Autoclear} is checked.



See also @{" Keys " LINK Keys}

@endnode


@NODE Autoclear  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Autoclear@{ub}

The Autoclear checkbox indicates if the @{" Search results " LINK listview} listview is to be
cleared every time you start a new Search or Anagram search.



See also @{" Clear         " LINK Clear}
         @{" Keys          " LINK Keys}
         @{" Configuration " LINK Configuration}

@endnode


@NODE Expected  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Expected@{ub}

If you set this gadget to Many, Zuppel will add new matches to the
@{" Search results " LINK listview} listview in bursts of 20. This shortens the total
searchtime.
If you set it to Few, you immediately see every new match in the Search
results listview.

If you expect less than 20 matches set it to Few so you don't have to wait
until Zuppel has searched the whole @{" Wordlist " LINK Wordlist}.



See also @{" Keys          " LINK Keys}
         @{" Configuration " LINK Configuration}

@endnode


@NODE Info  "Zuppel Guide  -  Usage"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Usage - Info box@{ub}

The information box shows how many words were searched (equals the total
amount of lines in the @{" Wordlist " LINK Wordlist} if the search wasn't interrupted).
It also shows the amount of words matched the search pattern.
And last it shows the search time.

Pretty obvious stuff in here..

@endnode


@NODE Configuration "Zuppel Guide  -  Configuration"
@TOC Main

@{b}Configuration@{ub}

Currently the only way to change the configuration is to edit the ASCII
configuration file. The Zuppel.config file is stored in the same directory
as the main program.


My version of Zuppel.config looks like this (without the comments!!!) :


  Wordlist              | Tag for selecting the Wordlist
  Words.Dutch           | Path + filename of the startup-wordlist
                        |
  SaveResults           | Tag for selecting the SaveResults
  RAM:SearchResults.txt | Path + Filename
                        |
  Preload               | Tag for Preload default
  On                    | On = Wordlist will be loaded into RAM if possible
                        |
  Expected              | Tag for Expected default
  Many                  | Many = Many, Few = Few   ;)
                        |
  Autoclear             | Tag for Autoclear default
  On                    | On = Autoclear is checked on startup

@endnode


@NODE Examples  "Zuppel Guide  -  Examples"
@TOC Main

@{b}Examples@{ub}


1) OK. Let's say you're looking for a word consisting of 6 characters, with
   the 2nd character being an R and the 4th character being an A. Enter in
   the Search pattern gadget the following:

     .r.a..

   Make sure the Searchmode gadget indicates Normal and click Search.


2) If you're looking for words beginning with a T and ending with ING,
   enter the following search pattern:

     t*ing

   Set the Searchmode to Normal and click Search.


3) If you're looking for all words containg the characters TIC, enter the
   following:

     *tic*

   Set the Searchmode to Normal and click Search.


4) If you're looking for all words containg the characters T, I and C, with
   the T before the I and the I before the C, enter the following:

     *t*i*c*

   Set the Searchmode to Normal and click Search.


5) If you're looking for all words containg the characters TIC, ending with
   characters AL and one arbitrary character, enter the following:

     *tic*al.

   Set the Searchmode to Normal and click Search.


6) If you're looking for all words containg the characters SPTO regardless
   of their position, enter the following:

     spto

   Set the Searchmode to Anagram and click Search.
   The results for the wordlist Words.Dutch will then be:

     Search results for spto
     post
     pots
     spot
     stop
     tops


7) If you wonder if a word contains other words enter for example this one:

     onaanvaardbaar

   Set the Searchmode to Contain and click Search.
   The results for the wordlist Words.Dutch will then be:

     Search results for onaanvaardbaar
     a
     aan
     aanvaard
     aanvaardbaar
     aar
     aard
     ar
     b
     ba
     baar
     d
     db
     n
     na
     nv
     o
     on
     onaanvaardbaar
     r
     v
     va
     vaar


8) If you're playing Scrabble and want to cheat, enter the drawn chars:

     poiuetr

   Set the Searchmode to Shuffle and click Search.
   The results for the wordlist Words.Dutch will then be:

     Search results for poiuetr
     e
     ei
     er
     erop
     eropuit
     eruit
     et
     etui

     ...

     port
     porti
     portie
     pot
     poter
     pre
     prei
     pret
     pro
     prut
     pt
     puerto
     pui

     ...

     ui
     uier
     uit
     uitroep
     up
     ure
     ut
     utopie





I hope this examples are of any use to you. If not, contact me and ask
away!


@endnode


@NODE FAQ  "Zuppel Guide  -  Frequently Asked/Answered Questions"
@TOC Main

@{b}FAQ@{ub}

1) How can I tell if the search has been completed?

      Check the @{" Break " LINK Break} button. If it's still enabled the search hasn't
      finished yet.
      After each search the @{" Info " LINK Info} box is updated, during
      a search it is blank.


2) Why isn't the d#mn thing faster?

      Zuppel is slow (i.e. it could be faster) because the format of the
      wordlist is simple. This means you can use a lot of standard ASCII
      files as wordlist, but it also slows down the search algorithm. If
      I would decide to make the algorithm faster it would mean that all
      wordlists should be converted to a special Zuppel-format.
      Maybe something for the future..

      The only optimization without a complete rewrite of the searchroutine
      would be to intergrate the fetch and compare routines. Watch out for
      a possible next version for that.

3) Where can I find other wordlists?

      On the internet:
      gopher://gopher.lysator.liu.se/00/project-runeberg/dict/where


4) Is the source available?

      No. But don't regret that.. It's not really you want to see :)
      But I'm always available if you have questions concerning coding.
      Contact @{" Me " LINK Author} by E-mail preferably.


5) Will you release new versions of Zuppel?

      Only if I get some feedback from YOU OUT THERE!!!
      (No, I'm not lonely.. heheh..)

@endnode


@NODE Keys  "Zuppel Guide  -  Keys"
@TOC Usage

@{b}Keys@{ub}

All underscored (_) characters in the gadgetlabels indicate that you can
simply press the corresponding key on the keyboard to execute a function.

I don't know why, but here's a list of all defined keys..

                  p - Enter search pattern
            Shift p - Clear contents, then enter search pattern
                  s - Start Search
                  m - Cycle SearchMode        (not underscored)
            Shift m - Backcycle SearchMode    (not underscored)
                  b - Break the actual search
                  v - Save the Search results
                  w - Choose Wordlist
                  c - Clear Search results
                  a - Toggle Autoclear
                  e - Cycle Expected gadget
          Escape, x - Exit Zuppel

           Arrow up - Scroll Search results one entry upwards
         Arrow down - Scroll Search results one entry downwards
     Shift Arrow up - Scroll Search results 20 entries upwards
   Shift Arrow down - Scroll Search results 20 entries downwards

@endnode


